# Token burn guard

Alert the user **immediately** (before continuing) when any trigger fires. Use this exact prefix:

> **⚠️ Token burn alert:** [reason]. Recommend: [one concrete cheaper action].

## Triggers — warn before doing the action

1. **Disallowed subagent** — about to call planner/verifier/reviewer/Task for planning or review (use Opus terminal prompt instead). **Implementer subagent is allowed** — no alert for implementer alone.
2. **MCP call** — about to use any MCP tool.
3. **Second+ full-repo scan** — already read 8+ files this chat and user only asked for a small fix.
4. **Multi-phase scope** — user said "continue phases" / "remaining phases" without naming one phase.
5. **Browser verification** — about to verify UI via automation instead of asking user to check localhost.
6. **Long orchestration chain** — implementer → verifier or multiple implementer passes in one session without user opt-in.

## On alert, recommend one of

- New chat scoped to **one phase file** only.
- User runs terminal/browser checks and pastes results.
- Opus in terminal for planning/review; Cursor for a **single** implementer pass.
- Disable MCP in Cursor Settings if not already off.

## Session bookkeeping

At the **start** of substantial work, note in one line: `Mode: lean (no MCP; plan/review → Opus terminal; implementer OK)`.

If user says **"burn ok"** or **"use subagent"**, stop alerting for that chat.

## Why this project burned faster than LFwork

ND-Portfolio used planner/implementer loops, browser MCP, and one long multi-phase chat. LFwork likely used direct edits in shorter chats. Prefer the LFwork pattern here unless user opts into heavy orchestration.
